        How to write code when your compiler speaks <em>English</em>.
      </h1>

      <ol class="framing" aria-label="Three-line framing">
        <li>LID is the language.</li>
        <li>Claude is the compiler.</li>
        <li>Code is the output.</li>
      </ol>

      <p class="hero-lede">
        Modern coding agents write code that runs. What they miss is what you <em>meant</em> — the places where the agent assumed one thing and you had something else in mind. LID closes that gap. You write your design at a few levels of detail your agent can compile faithfully: the design is the source, code is the output, and an edit upstream rewrites everything below it.
      </p>

